{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2d1ad67f-8a83-4dc2-987b-f72dc3088add","content":"This is a common macOS + .NET MAUI issue. **The .NET Android build system does not use `JAVA_HOME` by default** — it has its own JDK resolution logic and expects the **Microsoft OpenJDK 17** that ships with the Android workload.\n\n### Fix (recommended): Use the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui   # installs Microsoft OpenJDK 17\n```\n\nThe workload installer places it at a path the build system automatically detects (typically under the dotnet SDK directory or `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home`).\n\n### Fix (alternative): Point the build at your Temurin JDK\n\nIf you want to keep using Temurin, add this to your `.csproj` (or `Directory.Build.props`):\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nVerify the exact path with:\n```bash\n/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17\n```\n\n**TL;DR** — `JAVA_HOME` is ignored by MSBuild's Android targets; set `JavaSdkDirectory` explicitly or install the MAUI workload's bundled JDK.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17c59480-21c3-495e-8bce-b283c6518d04","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me check if there's a known compatibility issue with .NET MAUI and certain JDK versions/distributions.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution (microsoft-openjdk) rather than other JDK distributions. Actually, let me think more carefully...\n\n.NET MAUI Android builds use JDK 11 or JDK 17 depending on the version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI requires JDK 17. \n\nThe core problem is likely that the user's Temurin JDK doesn't match what the .NET Android SDK expects—the build system typically looks for Microsoft OpenJDK in a specific location, and using a different distribution can cause compatibility issues even if the version number matches. requires JDK 17. Temurin JDK 17 should generally work. But there's a known issue where on macOS, the JAVA_HOME path format matters—Adoptium installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home/`—and .NET MAUI might look for the JDK bundled with the Android workload at a specific path instead. The most likely culprit is that .NET 9 or 8 MAUI ships with its own JDK, which can conflict with the system installation. Without seeing the actual error message, the most common problems are either the wrong JDK version, JAVA_HOME not being recognized by MSBuild's `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` variable, or the Temurin path issue on macOS where Homebrew or Adoptium installs to a non-standard location. The most common errors with .NET MAUI Android builds on macOS are version mismatches, path issues, or the build system not finding Java even when JAVA_HOME is set. Since the user has Temurin 17.0.12 configured and `java -version` works, the real culprit is likely that the .NET Android build toolchain doesn't automatically use JAVA_HOME on macOS—it needs the `JavaSdkDirectory` property explicitly set in the project file or build configuration.\n\nThe practical solution is to either use the Microsoft OpenJDK that ships with the .NET MAUI workload, or manually point `JavaSdkDirectory` to the Temurin installation path. skills/plugins that might have .NET MAUI guidance. Let me check.\n\nLooking at the environment context: the working directory is `/tmp/sv-f17bb942aad34993a87cc6d940b704c7` and the directory contents are unavailable. It's not a git repo, so this is purely a knowledge question about a blank workspace.\n\nThe core issue is likely that **.NET MAUI Android builds on macOS don't automatically respect JAVA_HOME** — the build system has its own JDK detection logic. The